→ Client::process_message()\n    → decrypt_with_mik() → storage.store_received_message()\n```\n\nThe MessageReceiver path (TUI client) does NOT use SharedSeenCache for inbound dedup — only TransportCoordinator does.\n\n### Existing helpers\n- `OuterEnvelope::to_bytes()` — bincode serialization, can be used for byte comparison\n- `bincode_config()` in lib.rs returns `bincode::config::standard()`\n- `SharedSeenCache` — operates on MessageID only, not relevant here\n\n### Test infrastructure\n- `crates/reme-transport/tests/http_auth_test.rs` has `build_test_envelope()` helper\n- `http.rs` tests use axum mock servers\n- `pool.rs` tests are unit-only, no HTTP mocking\n- No existing tests for fetch dedup behavior\n\n## Design Requirements\n\n1. **Derive PartialEq + Eq on OuterEnvelope** so we can compare envelopes cheaply\n2. **Change both dedup sites** to detect conflicts: if two envelopes share `message_id` but differ in content, preserve all distinct variants\n3. **Return type stays Vec&lt;OuterEnvelope&gt;** — all distinct variants are flattened into the vec. The consumer (decrypt_with_mik) will naturally reject tampered copies since they'll fail decryption. No downstream signature changes needed.\n4. **Log conflicts as warnings** — relay divergence is a security event\n5. **Extract shared dedup logic** into a helper function to eliminate copy-paste\n6. **Add tests** for conflicting relay responses on both HttpTransport and TransportPool\n\n## Key Design Decision\nThe return type should remain `Vec&lt;OuterEnvelope&gt;`. When conflicts exist, all distinct variants are included. The decryption layer already handles invalid envelopes (they fail to decrypt). This means NO downstream API changes — the fix is entirely within the transport aggregation.\n\n## Questions to address in the plan\n- Where should the shared dedup helper live? (likely in the transport crate's lib.rs or a new dedup module)\n- What's the function signature for the helper?\n- How to test this with the